          <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Columbia <add>S.C.</add></placeName> <date>March 12<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1848</date></p>
          <p>Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I throw aside all manner of reserve<lb/> and address you for the purpose of gaining informa&#45;<lb/>tion on a certain Chapter in the Holy Book&#59; had it not<lb/> been pointed out to me by a Revd gentleman of the<lb/> Christian denomination&#44; with a view to obtain <hi rend="underline">his end</hi>.<lb/> I do not think I would have encroached upon your time&#44;<lb/> but as it does come up in the form of a strong argument<lb/> as he remarks in <hi rend="underline">his favor</hi>&#44; I would be pleased to hear your<lb/> views in regards to it.  I venture&#44; or rather choose not to enter<lb/> into argument until I hear from you feeling certain that one<lb/> so able and distinguished as yourself&#44; one so well versed in<lb/> biblical lore can easily explain it.  I have reference to the<lb/> 53 chapter of Isaiah&#44; a gentleman by the name of <persName>Abrahams</persName> from <placeName>New York</placeName> endeavored to explain it in the Sunday School<lb/> but his explanation was not satisfactory to me&#44; <hi rend="underline">not that I</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">doubt</hi> for I am a Jew&#44; a real Israelite in every sense<lb/> of the word&#44; and proud am I of the name.  There is<lb/> another circumstance connected with this chapter which<lb/> casts a gloom over me <sic>when ever</sic> I see it&#44; in confidence<lb/> I reveal it&#59; my brother in law &#40;<persName>Mr Isaac Woolfs son</persName> of<lb/> <placeName>Charleston</placeName>&#41; became <hi rend="underline">converted</hi> to Christianity on that very<lb/> chapter&#44; nor  was there any one who could sufficiently<lb/> explain it as to prove to him that the construction he placed<lb/> on it was false&#44; do you not think great good and benefit</p>
    <pb n="2"/>
          <p>would arise from it were you to give an explanation in<lb/> your valuable Advocate of Jewish Rights <sic>&#8220;</sic> the Occident&#63;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I should be pleased to hear from you by<lb/> return of mail&#44; or as early as convenient&#44; and if you differ<lb/> with me as regards a public explanation&#44; trust you will give me<lb/> your views in answer to this&#44; by so doing you will oblige many<lb/> of your friends here&#44; and none more so than</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)">Your Obt Sert &#38; Well Wisher</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">L. T. Levin</persName></p>
          <p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
